<section xml:id="FRQ1B-Part1">
  <title>FRQ 1B - Strings - Part 1</title>
  <introduction>
    <idx>frq1-methods</idx>
    <idx>frq1b-strings</idx>
    <idx>free response</idx>
    <p>From the 2025 Course and Exam Description: </p>
    <p><term>Free-Response Question 1: Methods and Control Structures</term>. Students will write two methods or one constructor and one method of a given class based on the provided specifications and examples. In Part A (4 points), the method or constructor will require students to write iterative or conditional statements, or both, as well as statements that call methods in the specified class. </p>
    <p>In Part B (3 points)<term></term>, the method or constructor will require calling String methods.</p>

<p>FRQ 1B requires the following skills:</p>
<ul>
<li>Complete a method or a constructor</li>
<li>Call String methods</li>
<li>Use if statements</li>
<li>Use a for loop or a while loop</li>
</ul>

<p>Teacher Insights</p>
<ul>
    <li>You do not need to include import statements. You can assume that any standard Java class is already imported.</li>
<li>You will NEVER print. If you think you need to print, you probably need to return something.</li>
<li>You will NOT need to write a main.</li>
</ul>
  </introduction>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b1-string-methods">
<title>String Methods</title>
<p>The following methods are on the quick reference, which you can view <url href="https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/media/pdf/ap-computer-science-a-java-quick-reference.pdf" visual="https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/media/pdf/ap-computer-science-a-java-quick-reference.pdf">on the College Board Website</url>.</p>

<figure align="center">
<image source="FreeResponse/Figures/frq1b-part1-string-methods-qr.png" width="100%" />
</figure>

<p>There are other methods in the String class that may also be helpful while writing FRQs, but it is important to remember that all FRQs can be solved using just the methods in the Quick Reference. If you use a method that is not on the Quick Reference, you must use it correctly to earn points.</p>
<p>The following activities can all be solved with just the methods in the Quick Reference.</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b1-emailparser">
<title>String Method - EmailParser</title>

<activity label="frq1b1-emailparser">
<statement>
<p>Write the getDomain method for the EmailParser class. This method is intended to isolate the server information from a full email address.</p>
<p>The getDomain method takes one parameter, a String called email. The method should identify the location of the "at-symbol" (@) and return only the portion of the string that appears after that symbol.</p>
</statement>

<program interactive="activecode" language="java">
<code>
public class EmailParser
{
    public static String getDomain(String email) {
        
        
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        // Test Case 1: Standard email
        String email1 = "student@school.edu";
        System.out.println("Test 1: " + email1);
        System.out.println("Expected: school.edu");
        System.out.println("Actual:   " + EmailParser.getDomain(email1));
        System.out.println();

        // Test Case 2: Different domain length
        String email2 = "john.doe@gmail.com";
        System.out.println("Test 2: " + email2);
        System.out.println("Expected: gmail.com");
        System.out.println("Actual:   " + EmailParser.getDomain(email2));
        System.out.println();

        // Test Case 3: Subdomain
        String email3 = "dev@api.service.io";
        System.out.println("Test 3: " + email3);
        System.out.println("Expected: api.service.io");
        System.out.println("Actual:   " + EmailParser.getDomain(email3));
        System.out.println();

        String email4 = "invalid-email";
        System.out.println("Edge Case (No @): " + email4);
        System.out.println("Expected: invalid-email");
        System.out.println("Actual: " + EmailParser.getDomain(email4)); 
    }
}
</code>
<tests>
import static org.junit.Assert.*;
import org.junit.*;
import java.io.*;import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class RunestoneTests extends CodeTestHelper
{
    private String[] email = {"nina@gmail.com", "user@me.co", "boss@mail.uk.edu", "a@work.com", "@nameless.com", "bad-input.com"};
    private String[] expected = {"gmail.com", "me.co", "mail.uk.edu", "work.com", "nameless.com", "bad-input.com"};
    
    @Test
    public void test0() {
        boolean passed = test(0);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test1() {
        boolean passed = test(1);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test2() {
        boolean passed = test(2);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test3() {
        boolean passed = test(3);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test4() {
        boolean passed = test(5);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    private boolean test(int i) {
        String desc = "getDomain(\"" + email[i] + "\")";
        String actual = "";
        
        try {
            actual = "" + EmailParser.getDomain(email[i]);            
        }catch(Exception e) {
            actual = "The code caused an exception";
        }
        
        boolean passed = getResults(expected[i],actual,desc);
        return passed;        
    }
}
</tests>
</program>
</activity>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b1-phoneprocessor">
<title>String Method - Phone Processor</title>
<activity label="frq1b1-phoneprocessor">
<statement>
<p>Write a method called <c>getAreaCode</c> that extracts the 3-digit area code from a formatted phone number. The area code will be the three digits between the parentheses.</p>
</statement>

<program interactive="activecode" language="java">
<code>
public class PhoneProcessor {
    public static String getAreaCode(String phoneNumber) {
        
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example 1: Standard Format
        String phone1 = "(800) 555-0100";
        System.out.println("Input: " + phone1);
        System.out.println("Area Code: " + getAreaCode(phone1));
        System.out.println();

        // Example 2: Different Numbers
        String phone2 = "(415) 888-9999";
        System.out.println("Input: " + phone2);
        System.out.println("Area Code: " + getAreaCode(phone2));
        System.out.println();

        // Example 3: Leading spaces (still works because of indexOf)
        String phone3 = "   (702) 111-2222";
        System.out.println("Input: " + phone3);
        System.out.println("Area Code: " + getAreaCode(phone3));
    }
}

</code>
<tests>
import static org.junit.Assert.*;
import org.junit.*;
import java.io.*;

public class RunestoneTests extends CodeTestHelper
{
    private String[] phones = {"(916) 555-1234", "(123)456-7890", "(000) 000-0000", "Phone: (510) 555-1212", "()"};
    private String[] expected = {"916", "123", "000", "510", ""};
    
    @Test
    public void test0() {
        boolean passed = test(0);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test1() {
        boolean passed = test(1);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test2() {
        boolean passed = test(2);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test3() {
        boolean passed = test(3);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void test4() {
        boolean passed = test(4);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }
    
    private boolean test(int i) {
        String desc = "getAreaCode(\"" + phones[i] + "\")";
        String actual = "";
        
        try {
            actual = "" + PhoneProcessor.getAreaCode(phones[i]);            
        }catch(Exception e) {
            actual = "The code caused an exception";
        }
        
        boolean passed = getResults(expected[i],actual,desc);
        return passed;        
    }

    private boolean stringMatch(String str1, String str2) {
        str1 = str1.replaceAll(" ", "");
        str2 = str2.replaceAll(" ", "");

        return str1.contains(str2);
    }
}
</tests>
</program>
</activity>

